00:04:27.240 --> 00:04:31.220
biological context, and implications for therapeutic development beyond

76
00:04:31.240 --> 00:04:32.160
KRAS G12C.

77
00:04:33.340 --> 00:04:34.460
These are my disclosures.

78
00:04:35.880 --> 00:04:39.640
So activating mutations in the RAS oncogenes

79
00:04:40.780 --> 00:04:44.400
we know are among the most important oncogenic drivers of cancer.

80
00:04:45.330 --> 00:04:49.280
They're found in about a third of human cancers, and they remain and rightly so, a

81
00:04:49.940 --> 00:04:52.800
major focus of cancer research and drug development.

82
00:04:53.340 --> 00:04:57.180
And after decades of real difficulty in drugging RAS, we've had some

83
00:04:57.740 --> 00:05:01.700
recent notable successes. KRAS G12C has provided

84
00:05:01.740 --> 00:05:04.120
proof of concept for a direct RAS inhibition.

85
00:05:05.580 --> 00:05:09.210
And in head neck cancer, HRAS mutation is being validated as a

86
00:05:09.220 --> 00:05:12.180
bonafide oncogenic driver in the disease.

87
00:05:12.200 --> 00:05:16.040
But these successes really only address a minority of patients.

88
00:05:17.820 --> 00:05:20.700
The majority of patients we know lie beyond G12C.

89
00:05:22.920 --> 00:05:26.380
So in the clinic, in reality, the majority of RAS mutant

90
00:05:26.440 --> 00:05:29.860
cancers, as I mentioned, harbor the non-G12 alleles,

91
00:05:31.120 --> 00:05:34.800
which remain comparatively undercharacterized and under targeted.

92
00:05:35.540 --> 00:05:38.820
In KRAS, for example, we have G12D and G12V,

93
00:05:39.800 --> 00:05:43.660
which exceed G12C in aggregate frequency, while NRAS and

94
00:05:43.860 --> 00:05:46.000
HRAS remain comparatively undercharacterized.

95
00:05:46.740 --> 00:05:50.420
This creates an important unmet biological and therapeutic need.

96
00:05:52.040 --> 00:05:55.800
So while we have undoubtedly made really significant progress in RAS

97
00:05:55.860 --> 00:05:58.980
targeting, we've really only addressed a fraction of the problem.

98
00:05:59.960 --> 00:06:03.660
Next generation RAS strategies really require broader

99
00:06:03.820 --> 00:06:07.210
biological prioritization. And to address this,

100
00:06:07.700 --> 00:06:10.860
we performed a large-scale pan-cancer

101
00:06:10.880 --> 00:06:13.430
analysis using AACR Project

102
00:06:13.480 --> 00:06:17.288
Genie.So

103
00:06:17.448 --> 00:06:19.308
I'm presenting data from version 19.

104
00:06:20.088 --> 00:06:23.968
We analyzed over 271,000 tumor samples

105
00:06:24.008 --> 00:06:27.928
in over 220,000 patients. As we all know, this is a

106
00:06:27.968 --> 00:06:30.508
pan-cancer, multi-institutional data set.

107
00:06:31.488 --> 00:06:35.328
And we focused on non G12C RAS alleles across

108
00:06:35.348 --> 00:06:37.948
KRAS, NRAS, and HRAS.

109
00:06:39.448 --> 00:06:40.468
We analyzed

110
00:06:42.148 --> 00:06:45.068
with regards to allele prevalence by tumor lineage,

111
00:06:46.068 --> 00:06:47.988
by tumor lineage distribution,

112
00:06:49.188 --> 00:06:52.268
and we analyzed co-mutation architecture.

113
00:06:54.628 --> 00:06:58.208
And so we hypothesized that RAS isoform are biologically distinct

114
00:06:58.328 --> 00:07:00.868
rather than being interchangeable drivers.

115
00:07:01.368 --> 00:07:04.568
And we aim to define the prevalence and co-mutational

116
00:07:04.648 --> 00:07:06.948
signatures of rare RAS alleles,

117
00:07:07.908 --> 00:07:11.568
to ultimately inform next-generation clinical trial

118
00:07:11.588 --> 00:07:11.988
design.

119
00:07:15.888 --> 00:07:19.868
So we began with KRAS, whereas we know the current therapeutic success is

120
00:07:19.908 --> 00:07:23.828
centered largely around G12 and G12C until very recently.

121
00:07:25.308 --> 00:07:27.368
So when we look across Genie,

122
00:07:28.488 --> 00:07:32.348
what becomes immediately clear actually is that these so-called rare

123
00:07:32.408 --> 00:07:34.308
KRAS alleles are not rare at all.

124
00:07:35.108 --> 00:07:39.048
And across approximately 42,000 KRAS

125
00:07:39.148 --> 00:07:43.088
altered tumors, non G12C alleles clearly dominate.

126
00:07:44.268 --> 00:07:48.088
KRAS alterations were found in 16% of tumor

127
00:07:48.188 --> 00:07:48.808
samples.

128
00:07:50.908 --> 00:07:51.508
Importantly,

129
00:07:52.788 --> 00:07:55.588
non G12C alleles dominated KRAS

130
00:07:56.288 --> 00:07:59.728
disease. G12D and G12V

131
00:08:00.288 --> 00:08:03.248
comprise of approximately 60% of KRAS mutations,

132
00:08:04.188 --> 00:08:07.248
whereas G12C comprise roughly 16%.

133
00:08:10.608 --> 00:08:14.168
The next question we asked was whether these alleles would distribute randomly

134
00:08:14.208 --> 00:08:18.198
among different tumor types or whether they reflected

135
00:08:18.428 --> 00:08:20.188
some distinct lineage biology.

136
00:08:21.108 --> 00:08:25.088
So interestingly, what we observed is that there was clear lineage specificity.

137
00:08:25.328 --> 00:08:26.208
As you can see here,

138
00:08:27.048 --> 00:08:30.748
G12D and G12V were broadly distributed

139
00:08:30.788 --> 00:08:34.369
across epithelial cancers such as pancreatic cancer, colorectal

140
00:08:34.428 --> 00:08:37.088
cancer, and lung adenocarcinoma.

141
00:08:37.129 --> 00:08:40.629
G12C and G12A were

142
00:08:40.668 --> 00:08:43.468
largely lung adenocarcinoma enriched.

143
00:08:44.688 --> 00:08:47.888
G12R, apologies,

144
00:08:48.588 --> 00:08:52.408
wrong audience, was interestingly pancreatic cancer

145
00:08:52.488 --> 00:08:53.168
restricted,

146
00:08:54.108 --> 00:08:56.048
while Q61

147
00:08:57.328 --> 00:09:01.168
was broadly distributed across tumor lineages including pancreatic cancer,

148
00:09:01.268 --> 00:09:03.668
lung adenocarcinoma, and colorectal cancer.

149
00:09:08.268 --> 00:09:11.728
So KRAS alleles, I guess, exhibited clear lineage specific biology.

150
00:09:11.808 --> 00:09:15.548
We next wanted to see if this extended to the co-mutation

151
00:09:15.608 --> 00:09:19.048
architectures. So we next examined co-mutation

152
00:09:19.088 --> 00:09:22.108
architecture within the Bioportr platform.

153
00:09:22.458 --> 00:09:25.988
And what we found was that KRAS co-mutation architecture was highly

154
00:09:26.068 --> 00:09:29.298
structured. So first we observed, as you can see

155
00:09:29.348 --> 00:09:33.148
here, lineage associated co-occurrence patterns

156
00:09:33.628 --> 00:09:34.908
including SMAD4,

157
00:09:35.888 --> 00:09:38.817
APC, CDK11, and KEAP1.

158
00:09:39.848 --> 00:09:43.508
Secondly, we observed mutual exclusivity with key

159
00:09:43.628 --> 00:09:47.037
pathway genes including NF1, PTEN, RB1,

160
00:09:47.608 --> 00:09:49.388
EGFR, MET, and BRAF,

161
00:09:50.788 --> 00:09:51.608
consistent with

162
00:09:52.628 --> 00:09:55.028
or suggesting even pathway redundancy.

163
00:09:56.028 --> 00:09:59.908
Altogether, these findings suggest that KRAS mutant tumors are shaped by both

164
00:09:59.948 --> 00:10:02.748
tissue context but also by pathway constraints.

165
00:10:04.268 --> 00:10:06.798
So we next turn to the rarer isoforms,

166
00:10:08.728 --> 00:10:10.088
starting off with HRAS.

167
00:10:11.388 --> 00:10:14.068
Interestingly, HRAS behaves very differently to KRAS.

168
00:10:15.008 --> 00:10:18.688
HRAS mutations were rare, occurring in less than 1% of tumors.

169
00:10:19.928 --> 00:10:22.597
When we looked at the type of cancers then,

170
00:10:24.108 --> 00:10:24.828
interestingly,

171
00:10:26.088 --> 00:10:28.668
unlike KRAS, HRAS showed selective

172
00:10:28.708 --> 00:10:32.668
enrichment in specific cancer subtypes such as bladder

173
00:10:32.728 --> 00:10:35.608
cancer, urothelial carcinoma, lung cancer,

174
00:10:36.387 --> 00:10:40.218
melanoma, thyroid cancer, colorectal cancer, and head and neck

175
00:10:40.248 --> 00:10:40.608
cancer.

176
00:10:41.888 --> 00:10:45.568
And at the allele level, codon 61 mutations

177
00:10:45.588 --> 00:10:46.188
dominated,

178
00:10:47.508 --> 00:10:50.308
with again additional G12 and G13

179
00:10:51.168 --> 00:10:54.778
variants, highlighting really a more heterogeneous

180
00:10:55.048 --> 00:10:58.628
mutation spectrum. We then examined

181
00:10:59.108 --> 00:11:00.888
whether this selective distribution

182
00:11:01.768 --> 00:11:05.208
was accompanied by differences in the co-mutation architecture.

183
00:11:07.128 --> 00:11:08.968
And what we found was looking at,

184
00:11:10.008 --> 00:11:13.428
in contrast to KRAS, HRAS really showed coordinated

185
00:11:13.528 --> 00:11:16.268
co-activation across multiple signaling pathways.

186
00:11:16.828 --> 00:11:17.768
You can see,

187
00:11:19.008 --> 00:11:22.728
as depicted here, you can see co-activation of

188
00:11:22.768 --> 00:11:26.508
PI3 kinase pathways, RAS signaling, RTK signaling,

189
00:11:30.228 --> 00:11:31.908
in addition to co-activation in

190
00:11:32.828 --> 00:11:34.148
MET, FGFR,

191
00:11:35.328 --> 00:11:37.808
alongside these MAP kinase and PI3 kinase pathway.

192
00:11:39.088 --> 00:11:42.568
In addition, alterations in NOTCH1 and RD1A and cell cycle

193
00:11:42.608 --> 00:11:46.188
regulators such as CDK4/6 suggest really a broader

194
00:11:46.308 --> 00:11:48.428
signaling and differentiation context.

195
00:11:50.108 --> 00:11:53.788
Then when ranked by effect size, HRAS co-mutations appear to really cluster

196
00:11:53.828 --> 00:11:56.588
around lots of differing pathways.

197
00:11:56.888 --> 00:12:00.828
Strongest signaling was being really in NOTCH1 and FGFR and

198
00:12:00.848 --> 00:12:01.568
AKT1.

199
00:12:03.008 --> 00:12:04.948
Altogether, this indicates that HRAS is

200
00:12:06.928 --> 00:12:10.668
not a dominant pathway-defining driver, but instead operates within a more

201
00:12:10.728 --> 00:12:13.388
coordinated multi-pathway signaling network.

202
00:12:15.628 --> 00:12:17.932
Finally, we move to NRASUm,

203
00:12:18.992 --> 00:12:19.492
NRAS

204
00:12:20.292 --> 00:12:24.102
really showed a distinct distribution, again, separate from KRAS and

205
00:12:24.192 --> 00:12:28.072
HRAS, with strong enrichment in melanoma and myeloid cancers,

206
00:12:28.272 --> 00:12:30.782
colorectal cancer, lung cancer, and thyroid cancer.

207
00:12:31.852 --> 00:12:34.772
At the allele level, as you can see on the right-hand side,

208
00:12:35.512 --> 00:12:39.282
Q61 was strongly dominant, accounting for roughly

209
00:12:39.532 --> 00:12:41.552
56% of NRAS mutations.

210
00:12:44.152 --> 00:12:47.212
We then examined the associated co-mutation architecture.

211
00:12:47.712 --> 00:12:50.572
And again, NRAS demonstrated something that was

212
00:12:51.472 --> 00:12:55.412
separate and different in contrast to KRAS and HRAS,

213
00:12:56.372 --> 00:12:57.212
where you can see here,

214
00:12:58.432 --> 00:13:01.752
NRAS co-mutation architecture really demonstrated both pathway

215
00:13:01.852 --> 00:13:02.672
redundancy

216
00:13:03.632 --> 00:13:07.232
and context-dependent cooperation, where you can see

217
00:13:07.472 --> 00:13:10.932
mutual exclusivity with EGFR and PI3 kinase or

218
00:13:10.952 --> 00:13:11.832
PIK3CA even,

219
00:13:13.032 --> 00:13:16.762
consistent with the upstream PI3 kinase pathway redundancy.

220
00:13:17.372 --> 00:13:21.132
Secondly then, there is a distinct co-mutation of significant clusters here,

221
00:13:24.532 --> 00:13:28.312
including gene specific for colorectal cancer and melanoma,

222
00:13:29.052 --> 00:13:33.012
including CDK and 2A and TERT alterations, as well as

223
00:13:33.032 --> 00:13:35.992
the broader RAS signaling modulating

224
00:13:37.252 --> 00:13:41.152
genes. Altogether indicating that NRAS really operates within a

225
00:13:41.212 --> 00:13:43.872
hybrid architecture rather than a single dominant model.

226
00:13:46.312 --> 00:13:49.032
So in summary, our data show that RAS

227
00:13:49.132 --> 00:13:52.932
isoforms are not interchangeable, but they define

228
00:13:52.952 --> 00:13:56.252
distinct biological architectures with codon and

229
00:13:56.292 --> 00:13:57.752
lineage-specific features.

230
00:14:00.072 --> 00:14:03.932
KRAS alterations, for instance, are broadly pan-epithelial,

231
00:14:04.832 --> 00:14:08.152
whereas HRAS and NRAS are enriched within

232
00:14:08.162 --> 00:14:11.332
more discrete lineage-specific contexts.

233
00:14:12.952 --> 00:14:16.332
We also observed clear differences in the co-mutation architecture,

234
00:14:17.172 --> 00:14:18.072
KRAS being

235
00:14:19.452 --> 00:14:23.352
enriched for more tumor suppressor alterations such as p53,

236
00:14:23.472 --> 00:14:24.192
SEK11,

237
00:14:25.132 --> 00:14:27.732
HRAS demonstrating more coordinated

238
00:14:28.072 --> 00:14:31.852
multi-pathway signaling activation, including

239
00:14:32.432 --> 00:14:36.132
activation of Notch, FGFR, and PI3 kinase, and NRAS

240
00:14:36.172 --> 00:14:40.052
reflecting more tumor lineage-associated patterns.

241
00:14:43.552 --> 00:14:47.412
These data are really consistent with preclinical hypotheses from

242
00:14:48.232 --> 00:14:51.912
the Haigis group and Dana-Farber, which support the concept that RAS

243
00:14:51.972 --> 00:14:54.912
isoforms are tissue-specific rather than interchangeable

244
00:14:54.932 --> 00:14:56.312
drivers.

245
00:14:57.872 --> 00:15:00.672
And collectively, really, these data support

246
00:15:01.232 --> 00:15:05.001
co-mutation-driven combinations and lineage-tailored

247
00:15:05.092 --> 00:15:07.892
strategies for next-generation RAS-targeted therapies.

248
