01:03:23.774 --> 01:03:26.974
Institute in Gaddy Getz's group, and I'm here today to talk about our work

1084
01:03:27.034 --> 01:03:30.874
leveraging Ultima Genomics PPMseq duplex whole genome sequencing

1085
01:03:30.934 --> 01:03:34.874
cell-free DNA assay to accurately detect clonal evolution over sequential blood

1086
01:03:34.894 --> 01:03:38.294
biopsies. And I'd like to thank the organizers and the AACR for giving me the

1087
01:03:38.354 --> 01:03:39.534
opportunity to present our work.

1088
01:03:41.154 --> 01:03:44.814
I have no financial relationships to disclose, and we receive funding from Ultima

1089
01:03:44.834 --> 01:03:45.294
Genomics.

1090
01:03:46.934 --> 01:03:50.694
So we know that cancer is an evolutionary disease that progresses over time,

1091
01:03:50.774 --> 01:03:52.614
particularly in response to treatment.

1092
01:03:52.774 --> 01:03:56.134
Clonal dynamics can play a large role in treatment response and disease

1093
01:03:56.194 --> 01:03:59.394
adaptation. Resistance mechanisms are often heterogeneous,

1094
01:03:59.654 --> 01:04:03.614
especially in late-stage disease, and we'd like to know how can we better

1095
01:04:03.814 --> 01:04:07.344
use longitudinal sampling over a treatment course to better understand these

1096
01:04:07.374 --> 01:04:08.903
patterns of cancer dynamics.

1097
01:04:10.114 --> 01:04:13.614
To this end, we've previously partnered with Dan Uhrich and the Rapid Autopsy Group

1098
01:04:13.654 --> 01:04:15.354
at MGH, Mass General Hospital,

1099
01:04:16.194 --> 01:04:20.114
to identify resistance mechanisms and the evolutionary history of a tumor at the

1100
01:04:20.154 --> 01:04:23.954
time of rapid autopsy. So using these 19, in this case,

1101
01:04:24.474 --> 01:04:28.444
tissue biopsies at end-stage disease, we've developed phylogenetic trees that

1102
01:04:28.534 --> 01:04:32.094
represent the history of the tumor from disease initiation all the way through to

1103
01:04:32.454 --> 01:04:36.154
multi-pronged resistance. In this case, as a breast cancer case, we can

1104
01:04:36.234 --> 01:04:40.004
see targeted resistance mechanisms such as ESR1, but also many

1105
01:04:40.454 --> 01:04:43.514
subclones with a high diversity and heterogeneity of different

1106
01:04:43.594 --> 01:04:45.354
resistance mechanisms.

1107
01:04:46.674 --> 01:04:50.374
But our question is: How can we reach this level of understanding premortem?

1108
01:04:50.914 --> 01:04:54.494
The rapid autopsy setting, these biopsies are difficult to obtain, and

1109
01:04:54.554 --> 01:04:58.474
also you can't adapt treatment course at this stage

1110
01:04:58.554 --> 01:04:59.134
of the disease.

1111
01:05:00.714 --> 01:05:03.774
We've also shown in previous work that liquid biopsies

1112
01:05:04.614 --> 01:05:08.354
can show a heterogeneous mix of resistance mechanisms as

1113
01:05:08.394 --> 01:05:12.374
opposed to tissue biopsies. In this case, in a colorectal cancer cohort

1114
01:05:12.414 --> 01:05:14.134
in which we partnered with Ryan Corcoran,

1115
01:05:15.214 --> 01:05:18.974
we sequenced tissue biopsies and only detected one or two

1116
01:05:19.014 --> 01:05:22.213
resistance alterations in about half of the cohort,

1117
01:05:22.514 --> 01:05:26.144
whereas in the same cohort with cell-free DNA, we detected over

1118
01:05:26.174 --> 01:05:30.094
three-quarters of the cohort had resistance mechanisms, and often

1119
01:05:30.134 --> 01:05:33.554
more than one. We found that these mutations were often in the

1120
01:05:33.914 --> 01:05:37.854
MAPK pathway, showing a convergence of resistance in these cases that would have

1121
01:05:37.894 --> 01:05:40.294
been totally missed had we only used tissue biopsies.

1122
01:05:41.754 --> 01:05:43.794
We'd also like to use whole genome sequencing.

1123
01:05:44.354 --> 01:05:47.894
So in these rapid autopsy cases, we sequenced using Illumina whole

1124
01:05:47.994 --> 01:05:51.694
exome. And in this case, we had a few samples here, and we built a

1125
01:05:51.714 --> 01:05:55.474
phylogenetic tree using the whole exome data, and we

1126
01:05:55.534 --> 01:05:59.274
found about six clusters, and often there were many alterations

1127
01:05:59.314 --> 01:06:02.134
clustered on a single branch. But when we sampled the same

1128
01:06:03.014 --> 01:06:06.914
samples with whole genome sequencing, we were able to really better resolve some of

1129
01:06:06.954 --> 01:06:10.774
these clusters. So we were able to pull these clusters out because there are so

1130
01:06:10.834 --> 01:06:14.694
many more mutations that we can detect that these groups of mutations can

1131
01:06:14.734 --> 01:06:18.714
travel together, and then we're able to identify unique driver mutations

1132
01:06:18.854 --> 01:06:21.974
on unique branches, and we can better track these clones over time.

1133
01:06:23.574 --> 01:06:27.054
So what more can we learn if we're able to pair these more informative liquid

1134
01:06:27.134 --> 01:06:29.724
biopsies with whole genome

1135
01:06:29.814 --> 01:06:33.334
sequencing? Current state-of-the-art in

1136
01:06:33.914 --> 01:06:37.394
cell-free DNA tracking comes in the form of a targeted panel.

1137
01:06:37.454 --> 01:06:41.394
These panels are often on hundreds of driver genes, or they're patient-specific,

1138
01:06:41.794 --> 01:06:44.694
meaning that a patient-specific panel from a

1139
01:06:44.994 --> 01:06:48.603
pre-sequenced tumor biopsy is used.

1140
01:06:48.954 --> 01:06:51.554
The problem with this is that due to the low content of

1141
01:06:51.574 --> 01:06:55.494
ctDNA in the tube, sometimes we can start to miss these

1142
01:06:55.514 --> 01:06:59.494
driver mutations, and then we miss information about all of the mutations

1143
01:06:59.534 --> 01:07:01.754
that are also traveling with those cancer driver genes.

1144
01:07:02.314 --> 01:07:06.174
In contrast, if we use Ultima Genomics' high-depth duplex

1145
01:07:06.234 --> 01:07:09.694
sequencing across these samples, we can use

1146
01:07:10.234 --> 01:07:14.134
the clones that we've already discovered in the tumor biopsies to then

1147
01:07:14.474 --> 01:07:17.374
track patterns of cancer dynamics over time.

1148
01:07:17.614 --> 01:07:21.564
We can identify these full clones that are moving, and we can also

1149
01:07:21.594 --> 01:07:25.384
look backwards and try to understand when these clones originally developed in

1150
01:07:25.434 --> 01:07:29.066
the life history of the cancer.Ultima

1151
01:07:29.166 --> 01:07:32.686
Genomics uses a flow-based sequencing technology that can increase the

1152
01:07:32.786 --> 01:07:36.746
accuracy of SNV calls. This allows for an extremely low base substitution

1153
01:07:36.786 --> 01:07:40.766
error rate. The error rates are more in these strings of homopolymers, which in

1154
01:07:40.826 --> 01:07:44.466
Ultima Genomics has come up with some tools to mitigate these error

1155
01:07:44.646 --> 01:07:47.585
models, including duplex sequencing technology.

1156
01:07:47.966 --> 01:07:51.846
So paired plus minus strand PPMseq technology additionally lowers the

1157
01:07:51.886 --> 01:07:55.746
sequencing rate. Both duplex strands are most on the

1158
01:07:55.806 --> 01:07:59.386
same bead, and so we're able to identify these

1159
01:07:59.726 --> 01:08:03.486
duplex molecules with a really high confidence, increasing the read

1160
01:08:03.546 --> 01:08:07.536
quality, even over Ultima's standard read quality, which is

1161
01:08:07.566 --> 01:08:08.226
high to begin with.

1162
01:08:10.686 --> 01:08:14.466
Additionally, we find that the molecules have a higher duplex yield,

1163
01:08:14.826 --> 01:08:18.566
so we're able to get more of these high-quality read calls.

1164
01:08:18.646 --> 01:08:21.387
And we see this in published data and in our data set as well.

1165
01:08:23.326 --> 01:08:26.936
So in collaboration with Ultima, we've developed our cloud-based pipeline that

1166
01:08:26.967 --> 01:08:30.666
we've used in many projects, including as TCGA whole genomes project.

1167
01:08:31.007 --> 01:08:34.887
We use the information from Ultima as to which reads are the highest quality duplex

1168
01:08:34.927 --> 01:08:38.016
reads, and then we call SNVs,

1169
01:08:38.366 --> 01:08:42.346
CNVs, purity/ploidy, and cancer cell fraction to start modeling the cancer

1170
01:08:42.387 --> 01:08:42.826
over time.

1171
01:08:44.366 --> 01:08:48.246
We also know using our model, PhyLogicNDT, that more samples and more

1172
01:08:48.286 --> 01:08:50.446
mutations increases its cluster resolution.

1173
01:08:50.507 --> 01:08:53.846
So in whole exome, we see there's a few tens of mutations and that we have high

1174
01:08:53.946 --> 01:08:55.887
confidence intervals in some of these clones.

1175
01:08:55.986 --> 01:08:59.387
But using whole genome sequencing, there can be thousands of mutations, and we can

1176
01:08:59.406 --> 01:09:02.547
be highly confident about which mutations are present in which clones.

1177
01:09:03.467 --> 01:09:07.246
We also use an MCMC algorithm to sample the space of trees, and

1178
01:09:07.286 --> 01:09:11.186
we can collectively come to maybe the correct

1179
01:09:11.246 --> 01:09:14.606
tree. And with whole genome sequencing, we can be more confident in this tree.

1180
01:09:15.746 --> 01:09:19.587
So in this study, we used a previously sequenced tissue and cell-free DNA set of

1181
01:09:19.606 --> 01:09:23.566
six breast cancer patients. We sampled the cell-free DNA over

1182
01:09:23.606 --> 01:09:27.306
time, and then we also have these tissue samples at time of autopsy.

1183
01:09:27.387 --> 01:09:30.846
Here we chose 24 of the cell-free DNA samples of the highest

1184
01:09:31.246 --> 01:09:34.887
tumor fraction, about 30%, to proceed with PPMseq sequencing.

1185
01:09:35.387 --> 01:09:39.346
And then we can use the previously sequenced autopsy and pre-mortem

1186
01:09:39.427 --> 01:09:41.906
cell-free DNA whole exome sequencing as a ground truth set.

1187
01:09:43.066 --> 01:09:47.007
So here we show we are able to reconstruct these phylogenetic trees

1188
01:09:48.306 --> 01:09:52.087
with the PPMseq data. This patient was an ER-positive breast cancer patient

1189
01:09:52.146 --> 01:09:55.246
treated with a PIK3CA inhibitor as well as a CDK4/6 inhibitor.

1190
01:09:55.766 --> 01:09:58.506
And we show that there are many more mutations on the branches of these clonal

1191
01:09:58.566 --> 01:10:02.486
trees. We also are able to identify the mutational processes

1192
01:10:02.526 --> 01:10:03.985
that are active along these branches.

1193
01:10:05.046 --> 01:10:07.846
Comparing to the whole exome sequencing, we show that we're able to

1194
01:10:09.226 --> 01:10:13.026
pull out some of the clusters that were not present in the whole exome

1195
01:10:13.066 --> 01:10:16.806
sequencing. For example, we found this P53 mutation in the whole exome,

1196
01:10:17.146 --> 01:10:21.086
but it was of too low of a cancer cell fraction to confidently assign to the

1197
01:10:21.146 --> 01:10:25.076
tree, whereas in whole genome sequencing, we're able to cluster that mutation with

1198
01:10:25.106 --> 01:10:28.266
another of a group of mutations, and therefore it is able to

1199
01:10:29.186 --> 01:10:30.546
end on the clonal tree.

1200
01:10:32.206 --> 01:10:35.826
In this case, in patient 1002, we see that in

1201
01:10:35.846 --> 01:10:39.526
cluster six, there's a large cluster of presumptive driver

1202
01:10:40.046 --> 01:10:44.006
